The climate conference, sponsored by the United Nations -- which has so far been characterized by unorganized assignments and mutual recriminations -- has returned under the light of the Friday ramp, as a result of the publication of a document highlighting ambitious greenhouse gas reductions over the next 40 years, with industrialised nations with most of the burden, in the next few years.
The text that could provide the basis for a final political agreement to regulate greenhouse gases highlighted the remaining obstacles, as long as it clarified the path to take.
But it has been seen as an important step in the negotiations that lack time, with more than 100 world leaders arriving next week in Copenhagen.
Written by a special United Nations working group, the text does not say how much rich countries would give to the poor to support climate warming, in the short term and in the long term.
And it offers a wide range of options for key issues, including the way in which developed economies and emerging economies could reduce their carbon production and what would be the upper limit of the global temperature increase that those responsible would be willing to tolerate.
It gives great flexibility to the process, said John Coequitt, Representative of the Sierra Club in Washington.
Michael Zammit Cutajar, who prepared six pages of the document, studied a 180-page negotiating text to focus on what the Executive Secretary-General described on the climate change of the United Nations, Yvo de Boer, as "full image".
It shows the guidelines for a possible agreement whereby industrial nations would collectively reduce their emissions by 2020 from 25 to 45 per cent compared to 1990 levels, while the main developing countries would reduce their emissions by 15 to 30 per cent during the same period.
Together, countries would reduce emissions between 50 and 95 per cent by 2050.
The European Union has also resumed negotiations on Friday, promising to provide $3.6 billion a year over the next three years to help the poorest countries adapt to the impact of climate change -- to sustain floods and droughts or to avoid deforestation.
However, on Friday, the same verbal alterations took place, which dominated the negotiations since last week.
Todd Stern, United States Representative for Climate Negotiation, rejected any discussion requiring greenhouse gas reduction by industrialised countries, compared with voluntary efforts made by major emerging economies, if these were not financed by developed countries.
This change is the signal that Obama's administration is becoming harder to China than Bush's administration was, two years ago.
The United States will not sign an agreement without the efforts and actions of the major developing countries, said Stern, who also regretted that the text did not insist on ensuring that reductions could be verified by external observers.
Stern made his comments an hour after the Chinese vice-minister of Foreign Affairs, He Yafei said that the US chief negotiator, either lacking "good sense", was "extremely irresponsible" for saying earlier this week that the United States would not help China financially to combat climate warming.
With the future economic trajectories of the major world powers at stake, defects have emerged both in the Third World and between the industrial world and emerging economies.
The current battle is more about saving individual economies than saving the planet, with China and the United States competing for their respective obligations, while the poorest nations insist that the two dozen most influential countries ignore scientific imperatives to act more courageously.
