75 per cent of working mothers have had occupational problems due to their maternity
Labour discrimination has increased in recent years, especially for women of young generations who want to be mothers.
This is what the study "Fécondity and professional career of women in Spain" by the CSIC in collaboration with the Instituto de la Mujer reveals.
The survey, conducted by 9,737 women 15 to 75 years of age, leaves no doubt as to whether 75 per cent of the mothers who work have seen their career limited due to maternity.
The study shows that there are many differences between the start of married life and the number of children, whether or not women work and the type of employment employed.
Those who have no activity outside the home, work part-time or have little stable work, get married early, have their first pregnancy earlier and have more children.
On the other hand, women with stable employment, mainly in the public sector, are retiring in marriage and first pregnancy, and have fewer children.
Women between 35 and 49 years of age have their first child, on average, 3.7 years of age after they are married. This figure goes to 4.1 among those working in the public sector. "These data show that women who have stable employment need more time in their lives to get it, which has led them to abandon the union and the arrival of children.
In addition, the type of employment exercised greatly influences maternity, but less the start date of common life," explains CSIC researcher Margarita Delgado.
The level of study is another factor that increases the gap between the age of marriage of women and their first child.
According to the survey, the higher the level of training, the more they get married and have their first child late.
The difference is also maintained among women of the same generation.
For example, in the group between 35 and 49 years of age, those who conducted elementary and higher studies were mothers for the first time at 25.1 and 32.1 years of age on average.
"Another distinuation also appears among women, depending on their level of study.
While those who have performed elementary studies marry and have their first child before finding a stable job, those who have conducted middle-level or higher studies invest this program and give priority to getting a stable job as a precondition for marriage and the arrival of a child," says Ms. Delgado.
